# Versioning Strategy Standards

This document defines standards for API versioning. Choose a strategy and apply it consistently across all endpoints.

---

## URL Path Versioning

Version in the path: `/v1/orders`, `/v2/orders`

### Pros

- Explicit and visible
- Easy to route at load balancer or gateway
- Cache keys naturally include version
- Simple for clients to understand

### Cons

- URL changes on version bump
- Can lead to path proliferation if many versions

### Example

```
GET /v1/orders
GET /v1/orders/{id}
GET /v2/orders          # New version, different contract
GET /v2/orders/{id}
```

### When to Use

- Public APIs with multiple consumer segments
- When you need clear routing and caching by version
- When URL stability is less critical than clarity

---

## Header Versioning

Version in Accept or custom header: `Accept: application/vnd.api+json;version=2`

### Pros

- URL stays stable
- Content negotiation aligns with HTTP
- Multiple versions can share same path

### Cons

- Clients must set header (easy to forget)
- Caching is trickier (Vary: Accept)
- Less visible in logs and debugging

### Example

```http
GET /orders
Accept: application/vnd.example.orders+json;version=2
```

### Custom Version Header

```http
GET /orders
X-API-Version: 2
```

- Document default when header omitted (e.g., latest or v1)
- Use consistent header name across all endpoints

---

## Content Negotiation (Accept Header)

Use media type for version and format:

```
Accept: application/vnd.example.v1+json
Accept: application/vnd.example.v2+json
```

### Format

```
application/vnd.{vendor}.{resource}.v{version}+{format}
```

### Example

```
application/vnd.example.orders.v1+json
application/vnd.example.orders.v2+json
```

---

## Version Lifecycle

### Stages

| Stage | Description |
|-------|-------------|
| Current | Actively maintained, recommended for new integrations |
| Supported | Maintained for compatibility, no new features |
| Deprecated | Sunset date set, migration encouraged |
| Retired | No longer available, returns 410 Gone |

### Transitions

```
Current -> Supported (when newer version released)
Supported -> Deprecated (when sunset planned)
Deprecated -> Retired (at sunset date)
```

### Deprecation Timeline

| API Type | Minimum Deprecation Window |
|----------|----------------------------|
| External, public | 12 months |
| External, partner | 6 months |
| Internal | 3 months |

---

## Default Version Behavior

When client does not specify version:

| Strategy | Behavior |
|----------|----------|
| Latest | Use newest stable version (can break clients on deploy) |
| Oldest | Use oldest supported version (safe, may miss features) |
| Explicit required | Return 400 if no version (forces client to choose) |

**Recommendation**: Default to oldest supported (e.g., v1) for stability. Document that clients should explicitly request newer versions.

---

## Implementation Checklist

When implementing versioning:

- [ ] Choose strategy (URL path, header, or content negotiation)
- [ ] Apply consistently to all endpoints
- [ ] Document default version behavior
- [ ] Define deprecation and sunset process
- [ ] Include version in OpenAPI spec (e.g., path or servers)
- [ ] Add Sunset/Deprecation headers for deprecated versions
- [ ] Maintain changelog with version history

---

## Anti-Patterns

| Anti-Pattern | Why It's Bad | Correct Approach |
|--------------|--------------|-------------------|
| No versioning | Breaking changes break all clients | Version from day one |
| Mixed strategies | Confusing for consumers | Pick one, use everywhere |
| Version in query only | Cache fragmentation, easy to omit | Prefer path or header |
| Too many versions | Maintenance burden | Deprecate and retire old versions |
| Default to latest | Deploy can break clients | Default to stable, require opt-in |
